SMO files

Description

Binary .smo files were structured as follows: Each file contains a 4-day recording or precisely 86400 consecutive 4s epochs. Each 4s epoch contains the following information: one byte character and 404 single precision floating-points, which represent, respectively: sleep-wake state of the 4s epoch as a character (wake = w, NREM sleep = n, REM sleep = r, wake w/ EEG artifact = 1, NREM sleep w/ EEG artifact = 2, REM sleep w/ EEG artifact = 3, wake w/ spindle-like EEG activity = 4, NREM sleep w/ spindle-like EEG activity = 5, REM sleep w/ spindle-like EEG activity = 6, Paroxysmal EEG activity in wake = 7, Paroxysmal EEG activity in NREM sleep = 8, Paroxysmal EEG activity in REM sleep = 9 ), EEG power density from the full DFT spectrum of the 4s epoch from 0.00 Hz to 100.00 Hz (401 values at 0.25-Hz resolution), the EEG variance, the EMG variance, and temperature. Temperature was not measured and was set to 0.0.

Path

Predicted EEG State

Description

Predicted state for each BXD. Prediction for 4 days every 4 seconds (86400 epochs). State are wake [w], NREM sleep [n], REM sleep [r] or artefact value of wake [1], NREM [2] or REM [3]. The 3rd day is replaced by the manual annotation

Path

Archived by Paul Franken, predictions are present within smo files

EEG and Behavioral Phenotypes

Description

EEG and Behavioral sleep phenotypes. Phenotypes contain:

  • activity
  • EEG
  • State

The directory Phenotypes/ contains the following information:

  • line (BXD lines)
  • mouseID (in format lines_mouseID)
  • room (room used for recording)
  • rec (recording time period)
  • worm (worm detection yes:1 no:0)
  • Phenotypes

Phenotypes were preprocessed using a pyhton script and saved with an extension with .quant for quantitative phenotypes and .qual for qualitative phenotypes

A deep description is present in the file: BXD_sleep.docx

A mean value per lines was computed and stored into the following files:

  • as text: AllPheno.txt
  • as Rdata matrix: SleepPhenotype.Rdata

Path

Data/LowLayer/Raw_EEG_Sleep_Activity_Phenotypes

Significant interaction genotype x SD for gene

Description

These files contain the significant interaction term between local genotypes and sleep deprivation effect. The SD effect map significantly on the local region (cis) and the interaction term for genotype effect on SD effect is also significant. Percentile indicates the value as 1-FDR, pvalint indicates the interaction term p-value from the model: Genotype X SD. intlogFC indicates effect of the interaction term. topmarker indicates the marker used. See this Rmarkdown

STAR alignment

Description

transformation of fastq files into bam files. Fastq files are filtered to remove low quality reads. STAR is used for alignment with the NCBI mm9 reference genome. Bam are then processed using samtools, piccard and GATK for indexing, add read group, mark duplicates, realign indel, and base recalibration.

Path

Scripts/LowLayer/GeneQuantification/

PreProcessBam.py

Variant merging

Description

Workflow to merge the public genotype available in geneNetwork and variant called using RNA-sequencing.

The variant that are highly different from the RNA-seq data are tag as unknown U

The scripts are within Scripts/LowLayer/VariantMerging/

  1. First we filter Variant calling file for variant that: pass the GATK filter, have genotype for 90% of BXD, have a quality of 5000

  2. the file from RNA-seq and GeneNetwork are combined

  3. we get An improbable marker files, containing GeneNework variant discrepency with RNA-seq (see GetGenotypeRegion.py)

  4. ImprobableGNMarkers.txt as U in GeneNetwork file

  5. Recombine files

  6. Filter for genotypes

  7. Rename File

  8. Change header to match general BXD name in phenotype files

Path

Scripts/LowLayer/VariantMerging

Input

VCF from RNA-seq; GeneNetwork Genotype

Output

BXD Genotypes

trans-eQTL mapping

Description

Trans-eQTL mapping was performed using . First gene expression and genotype were transformed into binary files.

Fastepistasis was run on each Tissu (Liver/Cortex) and condition (SD,Ctr)

Trans-eQTL were filtered to remove association within the same LD block, LD blocks were calculated by plink

Command sequence bellow is an example for the Cortex during control condition

Path

Scripts can be found here: Scripts/IntermediateLayer/trans-eQTL

Input

Normalized counts; Genotypes; RefSeq gtf

Output

trans-eQTL files [transeQTLs]

RefPosMiddle=RefSeqMiddlePosition.table


python Create_MAP.py $GenoF $OutF.map

python Create_PED.py $PhenoF $GenoF $OutF.ped

Get Genotypes Discrepancy between GeneNetwork and RNA-seq

Description

The script display as output the genotypes for the chromosome given in argument 4. Argument 1 is path to GeneNetwork genotypes Argument 2 is path to RNA-seq genotypes Argument 3 is path to combined file (see Workflow merging)

C57BL6/J genotypes are display as B DBA2/J genotypes are display as D Heterozygous genotypes are display as H

Genotypes in green are RNA-seq variant Genotypes in blue are GeneNetwork variant

Discrepancy in BXD lines are display as red genotypes and writing into stderr

Discrepancy are GeneNetwork genotypes surrounded by the other genotypes (B surrounded by D) in a window of 2Mb without any similar genotypes

You can edit the script to see smaller region

Example: python2 GetGenotypeRegion.py GeneNetwork.geno RNA_seq.vcf CombinedGenotypes.geno 5 2>>ImprobableGNMarkersResults.txt

Path

Scripts/LowLayer/VariantMerging/GetGenotypeRegion.py

Genes partial correlations

Description

A Rscript to generate a partial correlation matrix.

  • Example using the script to compute pcor for gene in cortex during Control (Cortex NSD vs Cortex NSD): Matrix<-BXDpcor(CNSD,cis_CNSD,CNSD,cis_CNSD,GenotypeMatrix,CORES=30,method=pearson)

  • The input file (Expression matrix: CNSD and cis-eQTL matrix: cis_CNSD) need to be formated to contain the same gene and to have a marker associated to each gene, preprocessing was performed with GetParialCorrelationForBXD.R

  • The method can be spearman or pearson
  • parallel,reshape2,matrixStats and RcppEigen packages are required

  • If you want to change between interaction or additive effect, edit model matrix in the CorResiduals() function

The output is a R matrix with gene-gene correlation value.

The Script require

An example is present here

Path

Scripts/IntermediateLayer/partial_correlation/BXDpcor_V1.0.1.R

Input

Expression Data; cis-eQTL File

Output

Partial correlation Matrix

Version

1.0.1

Genotype-SD interaction for transcript

Description

A limma pipeline that test if a gene fold-change after sleep deprivation that was map locally (using cis-eQTL fold-change) has a significant interaction term.

The pipeline use the following linear model: Gene Level = Genotype * Condition

Path

Scripts/IntermediateLayer/Allelic_Effect_On_FoldChange/Allelic_Differential_Expression_Final.Rmd

Input

Raw counts; Genotypes; $

Output

Genotype SD significant interaction

Genotype-SD interaction for metabolite

Description

An ANOVA pipeline that test if a metabolite fold-change after sleep deprivation that was map locally (using mQTL) has a significant interaction term.

As we have independent measurement between condition and multiple value for each BXD lines, we use the following linear model

The pipeline use the following nested linear model: Metabolite Level = Genotype/BXDLines + Genotype * Condition

Path

Scripts/IntermediateLayer/Allelic_Effect_On_FoldChange/Differential_Expression_Metabolites_FC.Rmd

Input

Metabolite level; Genotypes; mQTL

Output

Genotype SD significant interaction

Genotype-SD interaction for phenotypes

Description

A mixed model pipeline that test if a phenotypes fold-change after sleep deprivation that was map locally (using ph-QTL) has a significant interaction term. As we have dependent measurement between condition and multiple value for each BXD lines, we use the following linear mixed model (we didnt use lines as fixed effect to reduce the number of parameter used in our model)

The pipeline use the following linear mixed model: Phenotypes Level => fixed effect: Genotype * Condition; random effect: Mouse individual, we model a different intercept for different mouse. (using lmer: Phenotype ~ Genotype * Condition + (1|mID))

Path

Scripts/IntermediateLayer/Allelic_Effect_On_FoldChange/SDeffectOnPhenotype_FCdiff.Rmd

Input

Phenotype data; Genotypes; ph-QTL

Output

Genotype SD significant interaction

Gene Prioritization

Description

Script used for gene prioritization. Output can be found here: Data/HighLayer/GenePrioritization/*.html.

The script RmdTomd.R was used to run Scoring.Rmd on a remote cluster.

Example: Rscript RmdTomd.R -i Scoring.Rmd -c SD -t C -p 10000 -l 240 -k S -q 1000 -d 10 -n 6 -w Hk

  • -i Input Rmd path
  • -c Condition [SD or NSD]
  • -t Tissu cortex or Liver [C or L]
  • -l Phenotypes Number in phenotype file [integer]
  • -k Phenotype used, Sleep or Metabolite [S or M]
  • -q Number of permutation for FDR compute [integer]
  • -p Number of permutation used for QTL mapping [integer]
  • -d Discretization of the data in number of bins [integer]
  • -n Number of Cores, use mclapply [integer]
  • -w Weighting method, Henikoff [Hk] or Entropy maximization EXPERIMENTAL ! [MaxEnt]

Path

Scripts/HighLayer/GenePrioritization/Scoring.Rmd

Input

Normalized counts; Gene position; eQTL files; Genotypes; Differential Expression; Variant annotation; Polyphen2 scores; Mean Phenotypes; Mean Metabolites
